	''Segregation, albeit self-segregation, is an unacceptable basis for a harmonious community and it will lead to more serious problems if it is not tackled,'' the report said. The report recognized the role of different cultures in modern British society, but added that it was ''essential to agree some common elements of 'nationhood.' ''
	One of the report's 67 recommendations found that religious schooling reinforced separation and said that at least 25 percent of children should normally come from a different faith to the dominant one in the group.
	The report recommended that Britain adopt an oath of allegiance for new immigrants to show their ''clear primary loyalty'' to Britain. It said the pledge should include a promise to learn English and to obey British laws. The exact language should be a matter for public debate, the report said, but it recommended the Canadian version as a model.
	The Canadian oath, proposed by Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau in 1976 and introduced a year later, reads, ''I affirm that I will be faithful and bear true allegiance to Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II, Queen of Canada, Her Heirs and Successors, and that I will faithfully observe the laws of Canada and fulfill my duties as a Canadian citizen.''
